{% set basicEmbedCode %}<embed src="animation.swf" type="application/x-shockwave-flash"
       width="400" height="300">{% endset %}

{% set svgEmbedCode %}<embed src="diagram.svg" type="image/svg+xml"
       width="600" height="400">{% endset %}

{% set pdfEmbedCode %}<embed src="document.pdf" type="application/pdf"
       width="100%" height="600">{% endset %}

{% set objectAlternativeCode %}<!-- embed: no fallback if the resource fails -->
<embed src="chart.svg" type="image/svg+xml" width="400" height="300">

<!-- object: fallback content is displayed on failure -->
<object data="chart.svg" type="image/svg+xml" width="400" height="300">
  <p>Chart unavailable. <a href="chart.png">View as image</a>.</p>
</object>

<!-- Best: use native elements -->
<img src="chart.svg" alt="Quarterly revenue chart" width="400" height="300">{% endset %}

<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;embed&gt;</code> element provides an integration point for external content or applications, typically handled by browser plugins. It is a <strong>void element</strong> (self-closing) with no closing tag and no fallback content mechanism.</p>
    <p>Originally designed for plugin content like Flash and Java applets, <code>&lt;embed&gt;</code> has limited utility in modern web development. Unlike <a href="/docs/elements/native/object/"><code>&lt;object&gt;</code></a>, it cannot contain fallback markup, so if the resource fails to load the user sees nothing.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <p>In modern HTML, there is almost always a better alternative. The <code>&lt;embed&gt;</code> element should only be used when no other element supports the content type and you are certain the resource will load.</p>

    <h3>Prefer Modern Alternatives</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Use <a href="/docs/elements/native/iframe/"><code>&lt;iframe&gt;</code></a> for embedding HTML documents and web applications</li>
      <li>Use <a href="/docs/elements/native/video/"><code>&lt;video&gt;</code></a> for video content with native controls and captions</li>
      <li>Use <a href="/docs/elements/native/audio/"><code>&lt;audio&gt;</code></a> for audio content with native controls</li>
      <li>Use <a href="/docs/elements/native/img/"><code>&lt;img&gt;</code></a> for images including external SVG files</li>
      <li>Use <a href="/docs/elements/native/svg/"><code>&lt;svg&gt;</code></a> for inline vector graphics</li>
      <li>Use <a href="/docs/elements/native/object/"><code>&lt;object&gt;</code></a> if you need fallback content for a non-HTML resource</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

